{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493245","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493245"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T07:02:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T07:02:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1266"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1266","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1266"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.04,0.03,0.78,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1266"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"37549"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1266","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1266"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1266"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"22129"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"687"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2614"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2732"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42267"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"37549","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/37549"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old woman is brought into the Emergency Department by ambulance, after being found unconscious by her daughter at 6.00pm. She was last seen well at 4.00pm. According to the handover from paramedics, there were a number of empty medication packets and bottles found in close proximity to her. Hospital records indicate that she has a longstanding history of major depression, treated with escitalopram 20mg PO and lithium 900mg PO. She also takes tramadol 100mg PO BD and paracetamol 1g PO QID for chronic back pain, as well as candesartan 16mg PO for hypertension. On examination, her eyes open to painful stimuli and she exhibits a withdrawal response. She is making incoherent sounds. Her blood pressure is 104/66mmHg, pulse 84/min and regular, respiratory rate 8/min and SpO\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C/sub\u003E 85% on room air.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Urgent electrocardiogram (ECG)","Empirical therapy with N-acetylcysteine","Serum paracetamol levels","Rapid sequence induction and endotracheal intubation","Application of nasal prongs and oxygen delivery 3L/min"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer to this question is \u003Cstrong\u003Erapid sequence induction and insertion of an endotracheal tube\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is brought into the ED via ambulance with a presumed polypharmacy overdose. She exhibits a reduced conscious state (E2, V2, M4, GCS=8) with ventilatory impairment and peripheral oxygen saturation of 85%. Thus, the immediate priority should be securing a definitive airway as she is at risk of aspiration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELithium is one of her regular medications and it is likely that she has ingested a toxic dose. As lithium toxicity is associated with arrhythmias, performing an ECG is an essential cornerstone of this patient\u0027s initial assessment. Despite this however, establishing a definitive airway is a more pressing concern and should take priority.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEmpirical therapy with N-acetylcysteine should be given if the patient has taken a toxic dose of paracetamol (\u0026gt;10g or \u0026gt;200mg/kg, whichever is greater) and it is \u0026gt;8 hours after likely ingestion. This patient has been brought in approximately 2 hours following paracetamol ingestion, so empirical NAC is not indicated at this time.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe has likely ingested a significant amount of paracetamol and thus, serum paracetamol levels will need to be performed at some point. As the overdose was less than 4 hours ago, it would be appropriate to wait until the 4 hour-mark and then check serum paracetamol levels. As such, checking serum paracetamol levels immediately is not the right answer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer oxygen saturation at 85% is likely due to hypoventilation and some degree of airway compromise. Applying nasal prongs and delivering oxygen at 3L/min will not be helpful in this scenario, as it does not address the underlying issue of having a non-fasted patient who cannot protect her own airway. Therefore, intubation is a more appropriate course of action in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Airway management must take priority in any instance of diminished consciousness."],"references":["Baird-Gunning J, Lea-Henry T, Hoegberg LCG, et al. Lithium Poisoning. J Int Care Med 2017 May; 32:249-63."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"22129"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1266"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"22129","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/22129"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-07-01T11:06:20+09:30","updatedAt":"2023-07-01T11:06:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1266"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"37549"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"687","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/687"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Drug overdose","synonyms":["Overdose","OD"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-05-19T22:40:10+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-10T15:27:07+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"2"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4961","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4961"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:22:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-17T23:22:35+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"22"}